From: grante@hydro.rosemount.com (Grant Edwards)
Subject: Bootable floppy-based system...
Date: Tue, 30 Nov 1993 20:05:09 GMT

Before my latest effort to upgrade/enhance my Linux system with new
system-type stuff, I decided it would be cool to have a floppy that I
could boot and run from in case I broke something.

I don't mean just dd'ing the kernel onto a raw floppy, I mean having a
floppy with LILO, a kernel, a file system, directory tree, shell and a
few utilities.  So, I did fdformat, mkfs, lilo install, rdev'd a
kernel image, created a root file tree with /etc, /bin, /dev and so
on.  I created a few appropriate devices and copied a few files to
appropriate places on the floppy (init, getty, rc, fstab, fsck,
inittab, login, sh, mount, umount, cat, ls, mv, tar, elvis, rm,
more...).

Got everything set up so I could boot this floppy and maybe do a few
useful things to fix up a broken hard disk system.  I had about 20K of
space left on the floppy when I got done.

So I do a fastboot and shove the floppy in.  Oh happy day! LILO comes
up, loads the kernel from the floppy, mounts the floppy, and...
aaargh, I didn't copy libc.so onto the floppy, so none of the binaries
can be loaded.  It did give me a login prompt, but nothing else works.

Well, libc.so is a little over 600K.  By the time you put the kernel
(300K), libc.so (600K), a shell (220K), you run out of room on the
floppy for any useful stuff like tar, cpio, a text editor, etc.

Bummer.

I suppose I could try to find a simple bourne shell and statically
link it and some other file utilities so I don't need libc.so, but
I've got other stuff I'd rather work on, so I've dropped the
system-on-a-floppy scheme.  (I'll just be careful when changing system
files.)

Anybody else have any opinions on the usefulness and/or practicality
of having a bootable self-contained Linux system on a floppy?

--
Grant Edwards                                 |Yow!  On SECOND thought,
Rosemount Inc.                                |maybe I'll heat up some BAKED
                                              |BEANS and watch REGIS
grante@rosemount.com                          |PHILBIN..  It's GREAT to be
                                              |ALIVE!!

