From: wilcox@kpw104.rh.psu.edu (Ken Wilcox)
Subject: Re: Security
Date: 30 Nov 1993 22:00:53 GMT

Andy (pi92ae@lelle.pt.hk-r.se) wrote:
: Another point of view...
: We (the school) are thinking to set up a PC as a small linux box...
: connected to our NET, being able to run X and so on from our Suns
: (e.g. a complicated X emulator(but CHEAP) + some more).
: I have been looking around in the BIOS.. no way for it to protect the
: bios with password.

Upgrade your bios. All the versions of AMI bios ( I think) have password 
protection on it.

: Now assume that someone boots from his own disk.. what possible harm
: can he do to the net ?? If he trashes the local LINUX machine's HD, we
: have backups.. But what can he do with stuff ob the net and so on?

What could he possible boot from his own disk that could do more damage 
than booting Linux single user. Certainly MSDOG won't have anything that you
could harm it with that is less then the capacity of one disk.

: Can he send EMAIL from illegal host?

Anyone can do this from any where at any time.

-Ken Wilcox


