From: gt8134b@prism.gatech.EDU (Robert Sanders)
Subject: Re: Bootable floppy-based system...
Date: 30 Nov 93 23:06:00 GMT

grante@hydro.rosemount.com (Grant Edwards) writes:

>Well, libc.so is a little over 600K.  By the time you put the kernel
>(300K), libc.so (600K), a shell (220K), you run out of room on the
>floppy for any useful stuff like tar, cpio, a text editor, etc.

Well, you can get a smaller shell like pdksh(91K) or ash (MUCH smaller 
than bash or zsh, but not as user-friendly), a smaller kernel (my pl14 is
230K...leave out the things you won't need for system recovery),
and use libc-lite.  Note that if you copy libc using cp, it isn't
600K at all; it contains holes.  Try this:

root# du libc.so.4.5.4 libc-lite.so.4.5.4
272     libc.so.4.5.4
223     libc-lite.so.4.5.4

So, that's only 223K for libc-lite.

>I suppose I could try to find a simple bourne shell and statically
>link it and some other file utilities so I don't need libc.so, but
>I've got other stuff I'd rather work on, so I've dropped the
>system-on-a-floppy scheme.  (I'll just be careful when changing system
>files.)

Well, there are existing boot/root combinations out there.  Furthermore,
if you have two floppy drives, you can set up a small boot/root and
keep extra utilities on another disk.  Or, you could set up a disk
that loads your root filesystem into ramdisk and then you can insert
a /usr disk after removing the boot disk. 

These have all been done by various boot/root disk combinations.

